  "text": " The reason we don't see aliens is that as soon as they get to our level, they commit suicide. We look at the stars and wonder where everyone is. The answer might be that we are standing in a graveyard, but we haven't dug our own plot yet. The quiet is the aftermath. Number 3. The Shadow Biosphere When we search for life, we look for what we know. Carbon-based chemistry, liquid water, DNA. We scan the Goldilocks zones of stars. But this approach assumes that life, all life, follows the specific chemical pathway that happened to occur on Earth. Scientist Carol Cleland and others have proposed the existence of a shadow biosphere. This isn't just about aliens on other planets. This is about aliens here. The theory suggests that life may have emerged on Earth more than once. We are the descendants of the standard origin event, but there could be a second tree of life, chemically distinct, existing right alongside us. Microbes that don't have DNA. Organisms that process arsenic instead of phosphorus. Life forms that exist in the deep crust or high atmosphere that remain invisible to our detection methods because our detection methods are built to find us. Now, expand this to the cosmos. Dark matter makes up approximately 85% of the matter in the universe. Normal matter, the stuff we, stars, and planets are made of, is the minority. It is the cosmic scum on top of the pond. If physics allows for complex structures in the dark sector, dark life, then the universe could be densely populated, just not with baryonic matter. The horror here is one of intangibility. There could be a civilization existing in this room right now. Complex, intelligent structures made of dark matter could be passing through your body, through the Earth, through the Sun, completely unaware of us, and us of them. Or worse, they are aware. If the shadow biosphere exists, we are the blind men in a crowded room. We assume we are alone because we cannot see, but the statistical likelihood that only the 15% of visible matter can support complexity is arrogant. We might be the ghosts to them, insubstantial, wispy things that barely register. Or we might be the livestock. We have no way of knowing. We are vulnerable to forces we literally cannot touch. Number two, the berserker probe scenario. This is the militarized version of the von Neumann probe concept. A von Neumann probe is a self-replicating spacecraft. It goes to a star system, mines raw materials, builds two copies of itself, and sends them to the next stars. Exponential growth means that a single probe could colonize the entire galaxy in just a few million years, a blink of an eye in cosmic time. The fact that we don't see these friendly probes suggests that either no one builds them or someone built a different kind. The berserker scenario, named after the novels by Fred Saberhagen, suggests that the first civilization to achieve interstellar travel might have a strong incentive to ensure no one else does. They build kill vehicles. These are self-replicating probes programmed with a simple directive. Detect intelligent life. Extinguish it. Reset. These probes wouldn't need to be massive death stars. They could be small, stealthy, and dormant. They might lurk in the oar clouds of star systems, listening. Listening for radio waves. Listening for nuclear detonations. Listening for the telltale chemical signatures of an industrial atmosphere.",
